You? A Neanderthal? Never! <br><br>
You are correct that people will come to different conclusions after studying the different sums of the parts. Nothing is going to change that. I honestly believe that the war is just too big to study as a whole. My delight is reading and trying to understand how those that think differently than I. I, maybe ignorantly so, do believe that by knowing our past, we can SOMETIMES escape making the same mistakes again. Do I believe our involvement in 'Nam was wrong? Absolutely not! Do I believe anyone has all the absolutely correct answers? I doubt it. That doesn't keep me from trying.<br><br>
Have there been recent posts that have contributed destructive review of our government actions? (rule out any of Spatz's posts)I ask out of ignorance and nothing more. You can b/c with this if you wish. I will have to reread these latest posts again.<br><br>
I had, in the past, regreted my participation in the war. I do not now. I regret incidences that occurred while I was there. There are many times that I wish I was back in those times, for the life of me I do not understand. But the boiling cauldron I do understand.<br><br>
I am doing very well. Thanks for your concern. Thought much about you and the others at this site during my last layup.<br><br>
Each time we exchange posts, we learn more, it matters little if we agree. It's the communication that counts. But I found nothing that I could disagree with in your last post. We all have ghosts riding on our shoulders.<br><br>
My best to you, mon Capitan!
